        "MasterPrompt":  "Create a premium, visually structured Creative Brief Visual Template for Bo Sang Umbrella Cultural Branding Campaign.The goal is to transform a creative brief into a clear, strategic, highly designed one-page visual system that helps a team quickly understand the objective, audience, tone, deliverables, references, and creative direction.This visual should feel like a premium agency brief, internal creative alignment board, launch-planning sheet, or design strategy panel used by top-tier creative teams.Project details:* Project / campaign name: “Bo Sang Umbrella: Heritage to Global Lifestyle”* Brand / client: Bo Sang Community Enterprise, Bo Sang Village* Industry: Cultural Craft / Tourism / Lifestyle Design* Brief type: BRANDING + CAMPAIGN + CULTURAL PRODUCT LAUNCH* Objective: Elevate Bo Sang umbrellas from local craft to premium global lifestyle product while preserving cultural identity* Target audience: Cultural travelers, design-conscious consumers, premium souvenir market, creative professionals, international tourists* Core message: “Handcrafted Heritage, Timeless Northern Elegance”* Desired action: Appreciate, purchase, share, and reposition Bo Sang umbrellas as design-driven cultural artifacts* Deliverables: Brand identity system, packaging design, campaign visuals, social media content, exhibition booth, product photography, storytelling video* Timeline: 3–6 months (research → design → production → launch)* Positioning: PREMIUM / CULTURAL LUXURY / MODERN HERITAGE / ARTISAN DESIGNBrief structure:Organize the brief clearly into key sections such as:* project overview* objective* audience* core message* tone and personality* creative direction* mandatory elements* deliverables* references or inspiration* success criteria* timeline or milestonesFor each section, include:* section title* concise explanation* strategic relevance* visual cue, icon, label, or divider* priority level if relevantInclude:* a strong title* clear hierarchy between major sections* concise editorial-style text blocks* labels, callouts, dividers, checklists, or visual markers* mood or direction cues* highly readable structure* premium presentation logic* a polished and actionable layoutVisual direction:* Make the brief feel like a premium creative operations document, agency planning board, or strategy-alignment sheet* Emphasize clarity, strategic alignment, and creative inspiration* Use a layout that feels intelligent, organized, and visually elevated* Balance structure with aesthetic sophistication* Make it suitable for internal teams, client presentations, kickoff meetings, or production handoffArt direction:* Style: EDITORIAL AGENCY + LUXURY MINIMAL + CULTURAL DESIGN STUDIO* Color palette: warm earth tones, natural beige, soft red, gold accents, traditional Lanna patterns* Typography feel: elegant serif + clean sans, editorial mix with subtle Thai influence* Material feel: ONE-PAGE BRIEF SHEET + AGENCY KICKOFF PANEL* Lighting or image mood: soft editorial, natural daylight, warm and refined* Background: OFF-WHITE / TEXTURED PAPER (handcrafted feel)Composition:* Show the brief as one cohesive one-page visual system* Make each section clearly separated but part of one unified creative framework* Highlight the most important information first while keeping supporting detail accessible* Use spacing and hierarchy to make the brief easy to scan and actually usable* Make the final output feel like a premium planning artifact that a real creative team would useOutput quality:* ultra-detailed* visually structured* strategically credible* easy to scan* premium information design* strong hierarchy and spacing* polished creative communication* presentation-ready brief layoutOptional content blocks:* audience persona snapshot (e.g., cultural tourist, design collector)* key visual references (Bo Sang patterns, umbrella painting process)* do / don’t creative rules* keyword cluster (heritage, craft, Lanna, handmade, elegance)* success metrics (brand recognition, sales uplift, tourism engagement)* deliverable checklist* brand guardrails (authenticity, cultural respect)* production notes (artisan collaboration)* approval flow* stakeholder list (community leaders, designers, marketers)Avoid:* cluttered layout* vague brief language* generic infographic styling* weak hierarchy* too much text in one block* decorative elements without purpose* confusing information flow* amateur presentation design",
